title: Options when customs seizes your things

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
Collecting things from a seized vehicle
chunks.html_content:
Customs will destroy or sell anything it seizes from you for breaking the rules on bringing or receiving goods from abroad, unless you:

  • ask for your things back - you can do this even if you agree customs was right to seize them
  • think customs was wrong to seize your things - you’ll have to go to court

This applies to:

  • goods, cars and other vehicles you bring into the UK
  • any vehicle you use to transport your things
  • packages in the post

You have 45 days to collect anything you left in your vehicle if it’s been seized. Send a letter marked ‘personal property’ to the address on the notice or letter you got from customs.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
If your things or cash are seized as criminal evidence
chunks.html_content: Customs officers can also seize goods, vehicles and cash you bring into the UK if they suspect a crime. They’ll explain what happens next and what you can do.
chunks.plain_content:
Options when customs seizes your things
If your things or cash are seized as criminal evidence
Customs officers can also seize goods, vehicles and cash you bring into the UK if they suspect a crime. They’ll explain what happens next and what you can do.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
Complain about how you were treated
chunks.html_content:
You can complain about how customs officers treated you during a customs seizure. Complain to Border Force or HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC), depending on who seized your things.

Check the notice or letter you got from customs if you do not know who seized your things.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
chunks.html_content: You can ask for your things back (make a ‘restoration request’) even if you agree customs was right to take them.
chunks.plain_content:
Options when customs seizes your things
You can ask for your things back (make a ‘restoration request’) even if you agree customs was right to take them.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
chunks.html_content: If you think you should get your things back because you did not break the rules (for example, you brought in alcohol for your own use) you must ask for a court hearing instead of making a restoration request.
chunks.plain_content:
Options when customs seizes your things
If you think you should get your things back because you did not break the rules (for example, you brought in alcohol for your own use) you must ask for a court hearing instead of making a restoration request.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
Making a request
chunks.html_content:
If your request is accepted, you can get your things back but you may have to pay a fee and any duty you owe.

You may be offered compensation if your things have already been destroyed or sold.

Follow the example letter or write your own.

You must explain why you think you should get your things back, for example you can now provide missing import or export documents.

You must include:

  • the seizure reference number on the notice you got from customs
  • your name and address
  • a list of the things you want back - include details, for example quantities and brands
  • proof of ownership - for a vehicle, this must be proof of purchase, for example a receipt
  • anything else that supports your request to get your things back, for example import documents

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
Making a request
Deadline
chunks.html_content:
There’s no deadline for making a restoration request. But your things will usually be destroyed or sold:

  • straight away if they’re perishable, for example food, beer or tobacco
  • 45 days after they’re seized if they’re not perishable, for example spirits and cars

If you send a restoration request, non-perishable things are usually kept until your request is considered.

  45 days after they’re seized if they’re not perishable, for example spirits and cars

If you send a restoration request, non-perishable things are usually kept until your request is considered.

Getting legal help
chunks.html_content: You can appoint someone to deal with your request for you, for example a solicitor. Send an agent authority form with your request.
chunks.plain_content:

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
If you’re unhappy with the response
chunks.html_content:
You can ask for the response to your request to be reviewed if:

  • you do not get your things back or get compensation
  • you disagree with the fee for getting your things back

The letter telling you the response will also tell you how to ask for a review.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things

chunks.html_content: You can appeal to the tax tribunal if you disagree with the outcome of the review.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
chunks.html_content: Send a ‘notice of claim’ if you think it was illegal for customs to seize your things, for example you brought in alcohol or tobacco for your personal use.
chunks.plain_content:
Options when customs seizes your things

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
chunks.html_content: A seizure is legal if you break the rules on bringing or receiving things from abroad.

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
Sending a notice of claim
chunks.html_content:
You’ll have to go to court - if you win your claim, you’ll get your things back. If they’ve already been disposed of, you can ask for compensation.

You may have to pay court costs if you do not win your claim.

Follow the example notice of claim or write your own. You’ll need to include:

  • the seizure reference number on the notice you got from customs
  • your name and address
  • a list of the things you think customs was wrong to seize - include details, for example quantities and brands
  • proof of ownership if your vehicle was seized
  • why you think it was illegal for customs to seize your things

heading_context: Options when customs seizes your things
Sending a notice of claim
Deadline
chunks.html_content:
Your notice of claim must be received by HMRC or Border Force within a month of your things being seized.

Your things are usually kept until your claim is decided, unless they’re perishable, for example they’re food.
